result.execSummary:
The defendant Olijejuan Jelks was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin (<3g) [Modifiers: Second and Subsequent Offense], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)1.
  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin(>3-10g) [Modifiers: Second and Subsequent Offense], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)2.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Defendant Olijejuan Jelks in court with attorney James T Moczydlowski.  Megan M. Williamson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  
AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 5 YEARS, concurrent to COUNT 3 and consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 5 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 3 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  
Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 3 YEARS.
Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 
AS TO COUNT 3 :
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 5 YEARS, concurrent to COUNT 1 and consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 5 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 3 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  
Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 
Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on probation for 3 YEARS with the following conditions:
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION AND EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- Defendant must attend at least one Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  treatment or sobriety support group per week. 
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering or for distribution.
- No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm holster, or any body armor.
- Defendant may not live in any place where a gun is kept. 
- Defendant is not to possess case currency in an amount greater than $200.00.
- No contact with any associate or any member of a gang.
- Complete Parenting or Fatherhood course.
- Maintain full time work. 
- Court ordered Defendant to comply with all child support court orders. 
- No possession of more than 1 cell phone or more than 1 phone number listed under the Defendants name at one time. 
- Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not already done. 
- AS TO COUNT 1 AND 3:Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including
  the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. 
  Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due
  or civil judgment to be entered. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION ONLY:
- Court ordered defendant to serve 1 YEAR condition time in the House of Correction, without good time credit, with Huber for work and the Day Reporting Center. Court notes a strong objection as to electronic monitoring.  
Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

Court advises the Defendant that under Wisconsin Statute 302.113 the amount actually served may be extended, and that the Defendant could serve the entire bifurcated sentence in prison. The Defendant will be subject to certain conditions while on release to extended supervision, and a violation of any of those conditions may result in the Defendant being returned to prison.
